{{About|the medieval Arab geographer|other people named Al-Maqdisi or Al-Muqaddasi|Maqdisi}}
{{Infobox scholar | name = Muḥammad ibn Aḥmad Shams al-Dīn Al-Maqdisī (Al-Muqaddasī) | birth_date = c. 945/946 CE | birth_place = [[Jerusalem]] | death_date = 991 CE | death_place = [[Fatimid Caliphate]] | era = [[Islamic Golden Age]] | region = [[Muslim world|Islamic civilization]] | school_tradition = [[Abu Zayd al-Balkhi|Balkhi]] school | main_interests = [[Islamic geography]] | notable_ideas = {{Unbulleted list}} | major_works = ''The Best Divisions in the Knowledge of the Regions'' | influences = [[Abu Zayd al-Balkhi|Al-Balkhi]] | influenced = }}
'''Muḥammad ibn Aḥmad Shams al-Dīn al-Maqdisī''' ({{lang-ar|محمد بن أحمد شمس الدين المقدسي}}), also [[transliterated]] as '''al-Maqdisī''' or '''el-Mukaddasi''' , (c. 945/946 - 991) was a medieval [[Arab]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rahman |first1=Mushtaqur |title=Al‐Muqaddasī |url=https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007%2F978-1-4020-4425-0_8963 |website=Springer Link |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=1 |first1=2 |title=Al-Muqaddasi of Palestine : The greatest geographer of all time |url=http://muslimnews24.com/al-muqaddasi-of-palestine-the-greatest-geographer-of-all-time/ |website=muslimnews24 |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> [[geographer]], author of ''Aḥsan al-taqāsīm fī maʿrifat al-aqālīm'' (''The Best Divisions in the Knowledge of the Regions''), as well as author of the book, ''Description of Syria (Including Palestine)''. He is one of the earliest known historical figures to self-identify as a [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] during his travels.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Al-Ju’beh|first1=Nazmi|editor1-last=Heacock|editor1-first=Roger|title=Temps et espaces en Palestine: Flux et résistances identitaires|date=2008|publisher=Presses de l’Ifpo|location=Beirut, Lebanon|isbn=9782351592656|pages=205–231|url=http://books.openedition.org/ifpo/491?lang=en|archiveurl=https://archive.is/z3eDR|archivedate=19 Mar 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=al-Maqdīsī|first1=Muḥammad Ibn-Aḥmad|title=Riḥlat al-Maqdisī : aḥsan at-taqāsīm fī maʻrifat al-aqālīm ; 985 - 990|date=2003|publisher=al-Muʼassasa al-ʻArabīya li-'d-dirāsāt wa-'n-našr [u.a.] / The Arab Institute for Studies and Publishing|location=Beirut|isbn=9953441359|page=362|url=http://www.airpbooks.com/?url=en/BookDetails?BookID:1886|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>
==Biography== [[File:Regions of the Lands of Islam by al-Muqaddasi.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The regions of Islam in the tenth century, based on Al-Maqdisi's work]] Al-Maqdisi, "the Jerusalemite" was born in [[Jerusalem]] in 946 AD. He had the advantage of an excellent education and after having made the Pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] in his twentieth year, determined to devote himself to the study of geography. For the purpose of acquiring the necessary information he undertook a series of journeys which lasted over a score of years, and carried him in turn through all the countries of Islam. It was only in 985 that he set himself to write his book, which gives us a systematic account of all the places and regions he had visited. Le Strange comments of Al-Maqdisi's work: "His description of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], and especially of Jerusalem, his native city, is one of the best parts of the work. All that he wrote is the fruit of his own observation, and his descriptions of the manners and customs of the various countries, bear the stamp of a shrewd and observant mind, fortified by profound knowledge of both books and men." (From: Guy le Strange, 1890: ''Palestine Under The Muslims'' [https://archive.org/stream/palestineundermo00lestuoft#page/n32/mode/1up p.5] - [https://archive.org/stream/palestineundermo00lestuoft#page/n33/mode/1up p.6])
